ls- List directory contents
ls -l : Long listing format
ls -a	: Include hidden files
ls -lh	: -h  Human-readable sizes
ls -t  : Sort by modification time
ls -r  : Reverse order while sorting
ls -R   : List subdirectories recursively
ls -S   : Sort by file size
ls -1  : List one file per line
ls -d */	 : List directories themselves, not their contents
ls -F	 : Append indicator (one of */=@|) to entries
ls -l -a	: Using Multiple Options- ls-la, ls-ltr

Cd- Change the current directory
cd ..  : Move up one directory level
cd ~:   : Change to the home directory
cd -:  : Switch to the previous directory
cd /:  : Change to the root directory

pwd	Print the current working directory
pwd -L  : Display the logical current working directory
pwd -P  : Display the physical current working directory (without symbolic links)


Echo - Display a line of text
-n - Don't add a new line at the end
-e - Allow special characters like \n for new lines
-E - Don't allow special characters 

Cat -Concatenate and display files
-n  Add numbers to each line
-b - Add numbers only to lines with text
-s - Remove extra empty lines
-v - Show non-printing characters (except for tabs and end of line)
-E -show $ at the end of line
> used to create a new file and enter text contents from the terminal
>> use to append text contents to an existing file from the terminal

Cp - Copy files and directories
-r - Copy all files and folders inside a directory
-i - Ask before replacing files
-u - Copy only if the source is newer
-v - Verbose mode, show files being copied

Mv - Move or Rename Files
-i - Ask before replacing files
-u - Move only if the source is newer
-v - Verbose mode, show files being moved

rm - Remove Files or Directories
-r - Delete a folder and everything inside it
-i - Ask before deleting each file
-f - Force delete without asking
-v - Verbose mode, show files being removed


Touch - Change File Timestamps or create an empty file
-a - Update only when the file was last read
-m - Update only when the file was last changed
-t - Set the timestamp to a specific time
-c - Do not create any files

mkdir - Make Directories
-p - Create parent directories as needed
-v - Show a message for each created directory
-m - Set file mode (permissions)

man : The man command is used to display the user manual of any command that can be run on the terminal.

Grep - Search Text Using Patterns
-i - Search ignoring case differences
 (uppercase or lowercase)
-r - Recursive Search
-v - Invert Match

Awk - Pattern Scanning and Processing Language
-F - Field Separator
-v - Assign Variable

Cut - Remove Sections from Lines
-d - Choose what separates the fields Specify a Delimiter
-f - Select specific fields to display
--complement - Show all fields except the selected ones

Sort -Sort Lines of Text Files

Tail - Display Last Part of Files

Head - Display the beginning of a file

ps - Snapshot of Current Processes

Top - Display Linux Tasks

Df - File System Disk Space Usage

Du - File Space Usage

Free - Display Free and Used Memory

Kill - Terminate Processes

Zip - package and compress (archive) files

Unzip - Extract from ZIP archive

Tar - An archiving utility

Bash File Permissions and Ownership
r: Read permission
w: Write permission
x: Execute permission

0: No permission
1: Execute permission
2: Write permission
3: Write and execute permissions
4: Read permission
5: Read and execute permissions
6: Read and write permissions
7: Read, write, and execute permissions

chmod: Change file permissions
chown: Change file ownership
chgrp: Change group ownership
